answers: b'I\'m just not a white nationalist anymore. Not because I like jewry or faggotry or anything like that. But after doing deep reading into Nazi Germany and white nationalism I realized it was essentially all just Nordicism that regarded non Nordic white people like myself as inferiors.I\'d notice little Nordicist things that WN or NatSoc authors would write. I\'d ask people about them and they\'d give the usual excuses- so I mostly ignored them and rationalized it that it was in the past in a time of greater ignorance. Then I read "Next Time the World" by Rockwell and he exposed his unrepentant Nordicism in that book before he optically transitioned to a pan-European. I even read an article by William Luther Pierce talking about seeing mulattoes in Washington DC and he mockingly wondered if they were from Naples- Italy and had the Italian mafia collaborate with jews in his LARPy book The Turner Diaries. I reread Mein Kampf and read what Hitler had to say about Slavic people and people from Southern Italy: he thought they were mongrels.Then it hit me: my family from Italy are Neapolitan. You all consider me a bastardized- arab subhuman. I am the butt of the joke. It made me realize I don\'t really give a fuck about cucking to people that hate me and I don\'t really care about "the white race" at all. In fact by trying desperately to be included as "whites" which is a hated group- we just invite more ire from jews and browns'

answers: b"Which to me is one of the most practical answers to OP's question; gated communities. Ideally ones with mechanisms that make moving into or out of them more difficult than moving in/out of a suburb. A big part of the reluctance to create or maintain third places is racial tension- but also just a general fear of anonymous strangers. A gated community where all elements are known would reduce those fears.However the other big part of it; and /pol/ hates hearing this; is that third places only get the kind of foot traffic they need if they're in walkable districts. You need a solid body of customers and the best way to get that is have baked-in customers in close proximity who don't have to plan anything or make any big decisions to get there. But the other important thing is that you need regulars- and the best way to have regulars is to be in a neighborhood where proximity will draw the people who live near the place back in over and over and over again.Then- on any night where you have no particular plans- you can always feel safe taking a gamble on the local pub. It's a five minute walk and most nights you'll run into someone you know already. So that's what I'd angle for- gated communities with stringent entry restrictions that are walkable."
